    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory and store them in kernel variables. For each file, compute and return a compact summary only: 1) total row count, 2) minimum and maximum timestamp, 3) number of unique cmdb_id and list up to 50 unique cmdb_id values, 4) for metric.csv list up to 50 unique kpi_name with their counts (sorted by count desc), 5) for trace.csv list up to 50 unique trace_name with their counts (sorted by count desc), 6) for log.csv list up to 50 unique log_name with their counts (sorted by count desc), 7) for error_logs.csv return top 20 rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) as a sample. Limit all lists to the specified maximum sizes. Do not print full raw tables. Keep the returned output strictly compact and textual."
}

{
    "analysis": "Loaded telemetry files and produced a compact overview. Observations: metric.csv is large (322,439 rows) spanning 2022-03-21 08:30 to 2022-03-21 09:30 (UTC+8) with 59 unique cmdb_id values and many KPI names; trace.csv covers 2022-03-21 09:00 to 09:29 (UTC+8) with 27,656 rows and 36 unique cmdb_id (many trace.* features per pod); log.csv covers 09:00 to 09:30 with 1,822 rows and log.error_count / log.row_count present; error_logs.csv is empty. Next we must follow preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization. The immediate next step is to compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series (using the full series available) and then inspect the incident window (2022-03-21 09:00 to 09:30 UTC+8) for breaches. This will narrow metric candidates (component-KPI pairs) that show anomalies during the timeframe. No further analysis (traces/logs) has been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following and store intermediate tables in kernel variables but return a compact result: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, compute the global P95 threshold using ALL available rows for that pair from metric.csv and also record the total number of points in the full series. 2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: number of points in-window, count of points where value >= global P95, earliest timestamp in-window where value >= P95 (if any), and the maximum value in-window. 3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs sorted by count of breaches in-window (desc). For each returned row show: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_series_count, p95_threshold, in_window_count, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window. If there are no breaches for any pair, return the top 20 pairs by max_value_in_window instead. Limit output to these columns and at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 thresholds for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair and scanned the 09:00–09:30 window for breaches. The top-20 breaches returned are dominated by monotonic/static metrics (container_start_time_seconds, runtime StartTime, system.disk.total, large committed virtual memory values) that constantly exceed their P95 — these are likely false positives for runtime faults. Therefore we must narrow metric analysis to operational/resource KPIs (CPU, memory usage, network errors/retransmits/packets, latency, disk I/O, process metrics) to find real anomalies that could indicate the two failures. Traces and logs should be used after metric candidates are identified. No trace/log analysis has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan metric.csv for KPI names that likely indicate runtime resource health by selecting kpi_name values that contain any of these substrings (case-insensitive): \"cpu\", \"memory\", \"mem\", \"network\", \"transmit\", \"receive\", \"retransmit\", \"packet\", \"error\", \"drop\", \"latency\", \"delay\", \"disk\", \"io\", \"read\", \"write\", \"process\", \"tasks\", \"heap\", \"gc\". For each matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair do: 1) compute the global P95 using ALL rows for that pair; 2) filter rows within window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (UTC+8) and compute: in_window_count, breaches_count (value >= global P95 for that pair), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table of up to top 20 rows sorted by breaches_count (desc), then max_value_in_window (desc). For each row show: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_series_count, p95_threshold, in_window_count, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Also return the distinct matched kpi_name list and count of distinct cmdb_id matched. Limit all outputs to these aggregates (do not print raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We scanned metric.csv and computed global P95 thresholds for all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs, then scanned the 09:00–09:30 window. The top breaches were dominated by static/monotonic KPIs (container_start_time_seconds, runtime StartTime, system.disk.total, JVM memory/GC peak values) that continuously exceed their P95; these are likely metric-semantic false positives. We then performed a substring match to find health-related KPIs, but the top results still contained many static/runtime KPIs. Conclusion: we must exclude static/timestamp and JVM meta KPIs and focus only on genuinely dynamic operational KPIs (CPU usage/seconds, container memory usage, network error/retransmit/packet/drop counters, disk I/O read/write rates, fs_io, process/task states) and re-run breach detection (global P95 computed from full series) to surface real resource anomalies during the two failure windows.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, select KPI rows whose kpi_name (case-insensitive) contains any of: \"cpu\", \"usage\", \"user_seconds\", \"system_seconds\", \"mem\", \"memory\", \"rss\", \"working_set\", \"heap\", \"gc\", \"network\", \"transmit\", \"receive\", \"retransmit\", \"packet\", \"err\", \"drop\", \"latency\", \"delay\", \"fs_reads\", \"fs_writes\", \"io\", \"read\", \"write\", \"disk\", \"io_time\", \"tasks\", \"process\". Exclude any kpi_name that contains substrings (case-insensitive): \"start_time\", \"starttime\", \"runtime.java_lang\", \"garbagecollector\", \"memorypool\", \"system.disk.total\", \"committedvirtual\", \"totalphysical\" (these are static/timestamp/JVM-meta metrics). For the remaining (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs do: 1) compute global P95 using ALL available rows for that pair; 2) filter rows within the incident window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (UTC+8) and compute: in_window_count, breaches_count (value >= global P95), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table of up to top 20 rows sorted by breaches_count desc then max_value_in_window desc. Each row: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_series_count, p95_threshold, in_window_count, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Also return the distinct matched kpi_name list (up to 50) and the count of distinct matched cmdb_id. Limit outputs to these aggregates only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered metric KPIs to exclude static/timestamp/JVM-meta metrics and focused on dynamic health-related KPIs. The top candidates from that step are dominated by container memory RSS/cache metrics which show constant breaches throughout the 09:00–09:30 window (in_window_count = breaches_count = 31). This suggests either sustained high memory usage across many containers or metric semantics causing P95-based breaches. To localize the two distinct failures we must now use trace signals (which reflect service-level latency/error/throughput) to find temporal spikes or drops that mark failures, then correlate with metrics and logs. No trace-level anomaly analysis has been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze trace.csv to find temporal failure signatures during 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (UTC+8): 1) Identify all trace_name values that contain any of these substrings: \".error_rate\", \".duration_mean\", \".duration_p95\", \".row_count\". 2) For each matching (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair compute the global thresholds using ALL rows for that pair: P95 for error_rate and duration_*; P5 for row_count (use full-series P5). 3) Then filter trace rows to the incident window and compute for each pair: in_window_count, breaches_count (for error_rate and duration_*: value >= P95; for row_count: value <= P5), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), list up to 5 unique breach timestamps, and full_series_count. 4) Return two outputs (compact):\n   a) A table (up to 50 rows) of the pairs sorted by unique_breach_timestamps_count desc then breaches_count desc showing: cmdb_id, trace_name, full_series_count, threshold_used (label whether P95 or P5), threshold_value, in_window_count, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, unique_breach_timestamps_count, sample_breach_timestamps (up to 5).\n   b) An aggregate tally of breach frequency by timestamp within the window: for each timestamp in the window report timestamp and number_of_pairs_with_breach_at_that_timestamp, sorted by number_of_pairs desc (top 20).\nLimit all outputs to these aggregates (do not return raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found widespread trace.error_rate breaches across many service-to-service pairs during 09:00–09:30; most error_rate series have global P95 = 0.0 so any nonzero error rate in-window is counted as a breach. The breach-count timeline shows a clear peak of simultaneous breaches at 2022-03-21 09:11:00 +08:00 (644 pairs), with other high points at 09:10, 09:08–09:09 and a later cluster near 09:27–09:29. Metric scans so far are dominated by constant/timestamp-like KPIs and persistent container memory RSS/cache values that exceed their P95s continuously from 09:00 — these may be semantic/constant breaches. To localize the actual root cause events (there are two failures to identify in the 09:00–09:30 window), we need to correlate the trace peak timestamps with dynamic resource anomalies. Specifically, we should 1) identify the top peak timestamps by simultaneous trace breaches and then 2) for each peak timestamp find which dynamic operational metrics (CPU, memory working set/RSS, network error/retransmit/drop counters, disk I/O rates, fs_io_current, container_cpu_usage_seconds, container_network_*err*, etc., explicitly excluding static/timestamp/JVM-meta KPIs) deviate the most from their global P95 at that exact timestamp (largest value / P95 ratio). Those top metric anomalies at each peak will give candidate root-cause components and times to inspect further with logs/traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From trace.csv (window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 Asia/Shanghai), recompute the breach tally per timestamp for trace_name patterns containing \".error_rate\", \".duration_mean\", \".duration_p95\", or \".row_count\" using the same global-threshold rules as before (P95 for error/latency, P5 for row_count). Return the top 3 timestamps (with timezone +0800) by number_of_pairs_with_breach_at_that_timestamp. 2) Using metric.csv and restricting to dynamic KPI names (case-insensitive include substrings: cpu, usage, user_seconds, system_seconds, mem, memory, rss, working_set, heap, gc, network, transmit, receive, retransmit, packet, err, drop, latency, delay, fs_reads, fs_writes, io, read, write, disk, io_time, tasks, process; and exclude any KPI containing start_time, starttime, runtime.java_lang, garbagecollector, memorypool, system.disk.total, committedvirtual, totalphysical), compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using ALL available rows. 3) For each of the top 3 breach timestamps from step (1), extract metric values at that single timestamp and compute deviation_ratio = value / p95_threshold (if p95_threshold == 0, treat ratio as +Inf and mark accordingly). For each timestamp return a compact table of the top 10 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs sorted by deviation_ratio (desc). Each row: cmdb_id, kpi_name, value_at_timestamp, p95_threshold, deviation_ratio, and whether p95==0 flag. Also include a short aggregate: distinct cmdb_id count among the top-10 for each timestamp. Limit outputs to these aggregates only (no raw series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From prior steps: we loaded metrics, traces, and logs; computed global thresholds; scanned the incident window (2022-03-21 09:00–09:30 Asia/Shanghai). Trace analysis revealed a coordinated surge of trace.error_rate breaches with a clear peak at 2022-03-21 09:11:00 +0800 (644 pairs), with other high points at 09:10 and 09:08. Metric deviation checks at the peak timestamps returned many metrics whose global P95 == 0, producing infinite deviation ratios (these are sparse counters/metrics with zero baseline and thus need special handling). A few metric entries repeatedly appear in top deviations (shippingservice2-0 and adservice), but the prevalence of P95==0 means metrics alone are ambiguous. To localize root cause components for the two failures, we must leverage traces to find which downstream services experienced most incoming trace.error_rate breaches at the peak times (the root cause should be the most-downstream faulty service among those). The next step is to count, at the peak timestamps, which destination services (trace \"to_*\" targets) have the most error_rate breaches, obtaining top candidate services and their affected cmdb_id(s). This will let us pick candidate components to inspect further (metrics/logs) for the underlying reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the previously computed global thresholds, do the following (store intermediate tables in kernel variables but return only compact aggregates):\n1) Consider two timestamps: 2022-03-21 09:11:00 +0800 and 2022-03-21 09:27:00 +0800. For each timestamp, filter trace.csv to rows with that timestamp (UTC+8) and where trace_name contains \".error_rate\". Use the full-series P95 threshold computed earlier for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair to decide whether that row is a breach (value >= P95). If a pair's P95 equals 0, treat any value > 0 as a breach. 2) For each breached row, extract the target service name from the trace_name: if trace_name contains the substring \"to_<service>\" (e.g., \"trace.to_shippingservice-1.error_rate\"), extract the base service name before the dash (e.g., \"shippingservice\"); if it contains \"from_<service>\" or no \"to_\", also parse the component name similarly. 3) For each of the two timestamps, aggregate by extracted target service name and produce a compact table of top 10 services sorted by number_of_breached_trace_pairs desc. For each service row show: service_name, total_breached_trace_pairs_at_timestamp, distinct_cmdb_ids_involved (list up to 10), sample_trace_names (up to 10 distinct trace_name values). 4) Also return the total number of breached trace pairs at each timestamp (should match earlier tallies). Limit outputs to these aggregates and at most top-10 service rows per timestamp."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed many trace.error_rate breaches across the 09:00–09:30 window and produced a per-timestamp breach tally showing peaks (e.g., 2022-03-21 09:11:00 +0800 had 644 pairs). However, the later targeted check that filtered traces at the exact timestamps 09:11 and 09:27 and re-applied the P95 rule returned zero breached pairs — a contradiction. Possible causes: timestamp alignment/format mismatch (timezones or minute-flooring), different threshold table was used, or the exact matching logic filtered out rows (e.g., trace timestamps differ by seconds or timezone offset). We need to verify trace row availability and simple counts per minute first, and inspect sample rows at the suspected peak minute to reconcile the discrepancy before proceeding to metric correlation and log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Within trace.csv, restrict to rows where trace_name contains \".error_rate\" and timestamp in the window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai / UTC+8). Compute per-minute aggregates: for each timestamp (minute) return timestamp, total_rows (number of matching rows at that minute), count_value_gt_zero (count of rows with value>0), and breaches_count using the previously computed full-series P95 for that (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair (treat P95==0 as breach if value>0). Return the top 20 timestamps sorted by breaches_count desc (show these four columns). Additionally, return up to 20 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, p95_threshold) from the single minute that has the highest breaches_count to allow inspection of exact records. Limit outputs to these aggregates only."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor run returned per-minute aggregates for trace.error_rate across 09:00–09:30 (Asia/Shanghai). The top minute by breaches in that run is 2022-03-21 09:29:00 +0800 with total_rows=204, count_value_gt_zero=1, breaches_count=1. A sample of rows for that minute was returned but most shown values were 0.0 with P95=0.0. This contradicts earlier tallies (which showed large coordinated peaks at 09:10–09:11 with hundreds of breached pairs). The likely causes are inconsistent thresholding/interpretation of P95==0 (sometimes treated as breached for any nonzero, sometimes not), or mismatched minute-floor/timezone alignment in previous aggregates. Before correlating metrics or logs, we must identify the actual trace pairs that have nonzero error_rate (i.e., the true breached traces) at the minutes of interest so we can locate the downstream service components responsible. Currently we only know 09:29 has one nonzero error_rate; earlier high-count peaks need re-check but first we should inspect the actual nonzero trace rows to confirm real breaches and their cmdb_id/trace_name.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to rows with timestamp = 2022-03-21 09:29:00 (Asia/Shanghai / UTC+8) where trace_name contains \".error_rate\" and value > 0. For each matching row return a compact table (limit 50 rows) with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, and the full-series P95 threshold used for that (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair. If no rows match, return an empty table with the same columns. Keep output strictly compact (at most 50 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor run inspected trace.error_rate rows at 2022-03-21 09:29:00 +0800 and found a single nonzero error_rate: frontend2-0 trace.self.error_rate = 0.007874 which equals its full-series P95, so it was treated as a breach at 09:29. Earlier steps produced conflicting summaries: a prior tally suggested large coordinated peaks (e.g., 09:11 with hundreds of breached pairs), but a subsequent per-minute re-check showed almost all minutes had zero breaches and only 09:29 had a nonzero breach_count. This inconsistency likely stems from different handling of P95==0 (whether any nonzero is always treated as breach) or minute/timezone alignment in earlier aggregates. To move forward we must get an authoritative list of all trace.error_rate occurrences with value>0 in the whole incident window (2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 09:30:00 +0800). That will reveal which timestamps actually had real error activity and let us correlate to metrics/logs for root-cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to rows where trace_name contains \".error_rate\" and timestamp is within 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai / UTC+8) and value > 0. Return a compact table up to 50 rows sorted by timestamp ascending with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Also return two small aggregates: 1) the number of distinct timestamps that have value>0 within the window, and 2) the earliest timestamp with value>0 (if any). Keep outputs strictly bounded to these aggregates and the sample rows (no raw full-series dump)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have so far: 1) loaded metric/trace/log data and computed global thresholds; 2) initial metric scans flagged many static/timestamp-like KPIs and persistent container memory RSS/cache values that continuously exceed their P95s (likely metric-semantic false positives); 3) trace.error_rate exploration across 09:00–09:30 found only one true nonzero error_rate point (frontend2-0, trace.self.error_rate = 0.007874) at 2022-03-21 09:29:00 +0800, which equals its P95 and thus was a breach; earlier tallies that suggested large coordinated error peaks (e.g., 09:11) appear to be inconsistent with later per-minute re-checks — likely due to differing rules for handling P95==0 or minute alignment. Metrics alone are ambiguous due to many P95==0 cases and timestamp-like KPIs. To find the two failures we must broaden trace analysis to latency traces (duration_mean/duration_p95) and also inspect logs. The next step is to scan trace duration metrics (duration_mean and duration_p95) in the incident window using global P95 thresholds to surface real transient latency spikes that indicate failures and to identify their timestamps and candidate services/containers.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan trace.csv for trace_name containing \".duration_mean\" or \".duration_p95\" within the time window 2022-03-21 09:00:00 to 2022-03-21 09:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai / UTC+8). For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair compute the global P95 using ALL available rows for that pair. Then filter to the incident window and for each pair compute: in_window_count, breaches_count (value >= global P95), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), and max_value_in_window. Return two compact outputs: 1) Top 10 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs sorted by breaches_count desc then max_value_in_window desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, full_series_count, p95_threshold, in_window_count, breaches_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window. 2) A per-minute tally within the window of number_of_pairs_with_breach_at_that_timestamp (sorted by count desc) showing the top 10 timestamps (include timestamp and number_of_pairs_with_breach_at_that_timestamp). Limit returned rows to these aggregates only."
}

