    "analysis": "We have loaded metrics, traces, and logs and computed global thresholds. Metric analysis flagged many static/timestamp-like KPIs and persistent container memory RSS/cache values that continuously exceed their P95 (likely semantic false positives). Trace.error_rate inspection across 09:00–09:30 ultimately found only one true nonzero error_rate at 2022-03-21 09:29:00 +0800 (frontend2-0 trace.self.error_rate = 0.007874) which equals its P95 and was counted as a breach. Earlier summaries that reported large coordinated peaks (e.g., 09:11) were caused by treating value >= P95 when P95 == 0 (which counts zeros as breaches) or inconsistent handling. Trace.duration metrics also showed many pairs with P95==0 and max==0, yielding spurious breaches. To robustly find real failures we should look for meaningful reductions in traffic (trace.row_count) and nonzero error/latency spikes where P95==0 is handled as breach only when value>0. The next focused step is to detect row_count drops (use full-series P5 thresholds) across traces in the incident window to identify true failure time(s) and candidate downstream services.",
